<Document>
<name>N222 — Douro Valley Wine Country</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>N222 — Douro Valley Wine Country</h2><p><i>Portugal · N222, Peso da Régua to Vila Nova de Foz Côa</i></p><p><b>26 km of curves above terraced port-wine vineyards; longer arc continues to Paleolithic rock art.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>58 km (36 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Spring (vine flowering, May) and harvest (vindima, late September)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Blind curves, tractors during harvest, narrow shoulders, local drivers who know every bend</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>104</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Douro Valley is the world's oldest demarcated wine region (1756) and the only place port wine can come from. The N222 from Régua to Pinhão was named 'best driving road in the world' by Avis in 2015 — a marketing claim more than a fact, but the road earns it: 26 km of curves above terraced vines plunging to the river. Visit during harvest (vindima) in late September: families still pick by hand, treading happens in some quintas, and wineries open their doors. The Côa Valley rock art at the route's eastern end is the largest open-air collection of Paleolithic engravings in Europe — 25,000 years old, only discovered in 1994 and saved from a planned hydroelectric flooding.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Peso da Régua</b> — Capital of port-wine production. The Casa do Douro and the Museu do Douro both worth a visit; vineyard barge tours from the riverfront.</li><li><b>N222 'best road' segment</b> — The 26 km between Régua and Pinhão. Pull off at any of the dozens of viewpoints; terraced vines stepping vertically toward the slow olive-green river.</li><li><b>Pinhão Railway Station</b> — 1937 azulejo tile murals depict harvest, treading, and traditional life along the Douro. The line still runs (slowly) up to Pocinho.</li><li><b>Quinta do Seixo (Sandeman)</b> — Cliffside winery with port tastings and tours. Many quintas in the area open by appointment — visit Quinta do Crasto, Quinta do Vallado, or Quinta de la Rosa.</li><li><b>São João da Pesqueira</b> — Hilltop town overlooking the great bend of the Douro. View from São Salvador do Mundo chapel — perhaps the finest in the entire valley.</li><li><b>Côa Valley Archaeological Park</b> — 25,000-year-old Paleolithic rock engravings — auroch, horse, deer. Largest open-air collection of Ice Age art in Europe. Guided 4×4 tours from the museum.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
